* {{cite news |author=editorial |date=April 23, 1968 |title=Nature or nurture? |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |page=46 |url=http://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F20C14FB355D147493C1AB178FD85F4C8685F9}}
* {{cite news |author=. |date=April 23, 1968 |title=Geneticist: Didn't test Speck |newspaper=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] |page=8}}<blockquote>Dr. Pergament said he and Dr. Sato, a research fellow, had absolutely no connection with the Speck case and never examined Speck. The report was also denied by Speck's attorney, Public Defender Gerald W. Getty. "I never knew those doctors existed before I read about them in the paper," Getty said. Getty did say that a chromosomal test was performed on Speck, before Speck's trial, by a geneticist from outside the Chicago area. He declined to identify the geneticist, and he said the results of the test never have been disclosed. "It was agreed," he said, "that the results would not be disclosed unless I wished them disclosed. And I still don't." In any case, Getty said, the results could not be used in an appeal—since they were not part of the trial evidence. If anything, he said, they could only be used in connection with a new trial.</blockquote>
* {{cite news |author=. |date=November 26, 1968 |title=Getty tells Speck case plea basis; 10 issues are raised regarding trial |newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]] |page=A16 |url=http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/chicagotribune/access/586226742.html?dids=586226742:586226742&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI}}<blockquote>At the same time he made public reports from Vanderbilt University showing no abnormal makeup of Speck's chromosomes...<br />Getty displayed a letter of Sept. 26, 1966, relating that photographic evidence of 18 cells from Speck's blood showed no chromosome abnormality. He also exhibited a letter of last July 3, indicating that 100 of 101 cells in a sample of Speck's blood studied after the original tests showed the normal 46 chromosomes. The other cell had 45, regarded by the Vanderbilt investigators as having no significance.</blockquote>
* {{cite journal |author=Engel, Eric |month=September |year=1972 |title=The making of an XYY |journal=[[American Association on Intellectual and Developmental Disabilities|Am J Ment Defic]]|volume=77 |issue=2 |pages=123–7 |pmid=5081078}}—article by [[Vanderbilt University]] endocrinologist and geneticist Eric Engel, who performed two confidential chromosome analyses of Speck in September 1966 and June 1968. Based on mischaracterizations of XYY males as aggressive and violent criminals in the December 1965 and March 1966 preliminary reports by Jacobs, et al., Engel had made an unsolicited request in August 1966 to Speck's appointed defense attorney, [[Cook County Public Defender]] Gerald W. Getty, to confidentially karyotype Speck—which was repeated after false news reports in April 1968 that Speck was XYY.</ref> The series was echoed the following week by articles—again using Telfer as a main source—in ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' and ''[[Newsweek]]'',<ref>{{cite journal |author=. |date=May 3, 1968 |title=Of chromosomes & crime |journal=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |volume=91 |issue=18 |pages=41 |url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,841254,00.html}}
* {{cite journal |author=. |date=May 6, 1968 |title=Born bad? |journal=[[Newsweek]] |volume=76 |issue=19 |pages=87}}</ref> and six months later in ''[[The New York Times Magazine]]''.<ref>{{cite news |author=Stock, Robert W. |date=October 20, 1968 |title=The XYY and the criminal |newspaper=[[The New York Times Magazine]] |page=SM30 |url=http://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F50817F93E5F127A93C2AB178BD95F4C8685F9}}</ref>

In December 1968, the ''[[Journal of Medical Genetics]]'' published the first XYY review article—by Michael Court Brown,<ref>The first XYY review article, by W. Michael Court Brown, a physician and world authority on radiation biology and cytogenetics, was published in December 1968, the month he died at age 50. Court Brown had established the MRC Clinical Effects of Radiation Unit at [[Western General Hospital]] in [[Edinburgh]] in 1956, which was renamed the MRC Clinical and Population Cytogenetics Unit in 1967 (and subsequently renamed the [[MRC Human Genetics Unit]] in 1988). In 1962, Court Brown had been the first to suggest—based on findings of antisocial behavior in some institutionalized [[Klinefelter syndrome]] (47,XXY) patients and psychosis in some institutionalized [[Triple X syndrome]] (47,XXX) patients—that individuals with sex chromosome abnormalities could be held in law to suffer from diminished responsibility.
* {{cite journal |author=Court Brown, W. Michael |date=September 8, 1962 |title=Sex chromosomes and the law |journal=[[The Lancet|Lancet]] |volume=280 |issue=7254 |pages=508–509 |doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(62)90378-1}}
* {{cite journal |author=. |date=January 4, 1969 |title=William Michael Court Brown |journal=[[The Lancet|Lancet]] |volume=293 |issue=7584 |pages=57–58 |doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(69)91029-0 |pmid=4178806}}
* {{cite journal |author=Harnden, David G. |date=March 1969 |title=W.M. Court Brown |journal=[[Journal of Medical Genetics|J Med Genet]] |volume=6 |issue=1 |pages=107–108 |doi=10.1136/jmg.6.1.107 |pmid=4890463 |pmc=1468708}}
* {{cite book |author=Hsu, T. C. |year=1979 |title=Human and mammalian cytogenetics : an historical perspective |location=New York |publisher=[[Springer Science+Business Media|Springer-Verlag]] |isbn=0-387-90364-X |pages=41–42}}</ref> director of the MRC Human Genetics Unit—which reported no overrepresentation of XYY males in nationwide chromosome surveys of prisons and hospitals for the developmentally disabled and mentally ill in Scotland, and concluded that studies confined to institutionalized XYY males may be guilty of [[selection bias]], and that long-term [[longitudinal study|longitudinal]] [[prospective cohort study|prospective]] studies of newborn XYY boys were needed.<ref name="Court Brown 1968"/>

