In June 1969, the [[National Institute of Mental Health]] (NIMH) Center for Studies of Crime and Delinquency held a two-day XYY conference in [[Chevy Chase, Maryland]].<ref>{{cite book |author=Shah, Saleem A. |year=1970 |title=Report on the XYY chromosomal abnormality |location=Chevy Chase, Md. |publisher=[[National Institute of Mental Health|NIMH]] Center for Studies of Crime and Delinquency |series=Public Health Service publication No. 2103 |oclc=235264}} June 19–20, 1969 XYY conference.</ref> In December 1969, with a grant from the NIMH Center for Studies of Crime and Delinquency, cytogeneticist Digamber Borgaonkar at [[Johns Hopkins Hospital]] began a chromosome survey of (predominantly African-American) boys ages 8 to 18 in all [[Maryland]] institutions for delinquent, neglected, or mentally ill juveniles, which was suspended from February–May 1970 due to an [[American Civil Liberties Union]] (ACLU) lawsuit about the lack of [[informed consent]].<ref name="Pyeritz 1977">{{cite book |author=Pyeritz, Reed; Schreier, Herb; Madansky, Chuck; Miller, Larry; Beckwith, Jon |year=1977 |chapter=The XYY male: The making of a myth |editor=Ann Arbor Science for the People Editorial Collective (eds.) |title=Biology as a social weapon |pages=86–100 |location=Minneapolis |publisher=Burgess Pub. Co |isbn=0-8087-4534-4}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Associated Press |date=December 27, 1969 |title=Gene abnormality set for Md. study |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |page=B7 |url=http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost_historical/access/149109532.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI}}
